<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
<taxonomicName LSID="742A0C50-C87E-5CB3-B2E1-9E5FF1948E7C" authority="(Kirkaldy, 1909)" baseAuthorityName="Kirkaldy" baseAuthorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadatra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cicadatra persica" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persica">Cicadatra persica (Kirkaldy, 1909)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">General distribution: Southern Europe</emphasis>
: Bulgaria (this study), North Macedonia; 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Eastern Europe</emphasis>
: Russia (south European Russia); 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Middle East</emphasis>
: Iran, Israel, Syria, Turkey; 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Transcaucasia</emphasis>
: Armenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia; 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Central Asia</emphasis>
: Pakistan (summarised by 
<bibRefCitation author="Duffels, J P" journalOrPublisher="Dr W Junk Publisher, Dordrecht, Boston, Lancaster" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" refId="B5742783" refString="Duffels, J P, van der Laan, P A, 1985. Catalogue of the Cicadoidea (Homoptera, Auchenorhyncha) 1956-1980. Dr W Junk Publisher, Dordrecht, Boston, Lancaster" title="Catalogue of the Cicadoidea (Homoptera, Auchenorhyncha) 1956 - 1980" year="1985">Duffels and van der Laan 1985</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Sanborn, Allen F" journalOrPublisher="Academic Press / Elsevier, London, UK" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" refId="B5743532" refString="Sanborn, Allen F, 2014. Catalogue of the Cicadoidea. Academic Press/Elsevier, London, UK" title="Catalogue of the Cicadoidea" year="2014">Sanborn 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Kudryasheva, J. V." journalOrPublisher="Nauka, Moskva" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" refId="B5743179" refString="Kudryasheva, J. V., 1979. Lichinki pevchikh tsikad (Homoptera, Cicadidae) fauny SSSR. Nauka, Moskva" title="Lichinki pevchikh tsikad (Homoptera, Cicadidae) fauny SSSR" year="1979">Kudryasheva (1979)</bibRefCitation>
the western limit of distribution of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirkaldy" baseAuthorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadatra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cicadatra persica" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Cicadatra persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Mediterranean reaches as far as Sicily, but has not been confirmed by recent fieldwork with bioacoustic methods (Thomas Hertach, personal communication).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Distribution in Bulgaria</emphasis>
: Two male and one female specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirkaldy" baseAuthorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadatra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cicadatra persica" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Cicadatra persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Sliven are kept in the collections of SOFM and MZPW (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F5781283" captionText="Figure 23. Map with localities of Cicadatra persica in Bulgaria. Blue - data from collections." figureDoi=".figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/445615" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">23</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 24" captionStartId="F5781287" captionText="Figure 24. Altitudinal distribution of Cicadatra persica. The percentage of the recorded localities is displayed in 200 - metre altitude zones." figureDoi=".figure24" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447379" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">24</figureCitation>
). These data have never been published before.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirkaldy" baseAuthorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadatra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cicadatra persica" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Cicadatra persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also mentioned for Bulgaria in literature by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hava, Jiri" journalOrPublisher="Arquivos entomoloxicos" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="137 - 138" refId="B5743015" refString="Hava, Jiri, 2016. Cicadatra persica (Kirkaldy, 1909) new for Bulgaria (Hemiptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadidae). Arquivos entomoloxicos 16: 137 - 138" title="Cicadatra persica (Kirkaldy, 1909) new for Bulgaria (Hemiptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadidae)." volume="16" year="2016">
<normalizedToken originalValue="HÃ¡va">Hava</normalizedToken>
(2016)
</bibRefCitation>
from Sozopol on the Black Sea coast, but in this study, we find that the specimen was misidentified with an unusually coloured 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1790" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadatra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cicadatra atra" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Cicadatra atra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the large differences in body size.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
Using bioacoustic methods, we searched in Sliven and its surroundings under ideal weather conditions for singing cicadas and in suitable habitat (based on our own field experiences from North Macedonia (
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="5 - 15" refId="B5742945" refString="Gogala, Matija, Trilar, Tomi, 1998. First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song. Acta Entomologica Slovenica 6 (1): 5 - 15" title="First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song" volume="6" year="1998">Gogala and Trilar 1998</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="5 - 15" refId="B5742955" refString="Gogala, Matija, Trilar, Tomi, 2003. Video analysis of wing clicking in Cicadas of the genera Cicadatra and Pagiphora (Homoptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadoidea). Acta Entomologica Slovenica 11 (1): 5 - 15" title="Video analysis of wing clicking in Cicadas of the genera Cicadatra and Pagiphora (Homoptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadoidea)" volume="11" year="2003">Gogala and Trilar 2003</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="103 - 126" refId="B5742975" refString="Gogala, Matija, Trilar, Tomi, Krpac, Vladimir T, 2005. Fauna of singing cicadas (Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadoidea) of Macedonia - a bioacoustic survey. Acta Entomologica Slovenica 13 (2): 103 - 126" title="Fauna of singing cicadas (Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadoidea) of Macedonia - a bioacoustic survey" volume="13" year="2005">Gogala et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
)), but could not detect the presence of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirkaldy" baseAuthorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadatra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cicadatra persica" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Cicadatra persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Acoustic behaviour</emphasis>
: The song with intensive wing clicking was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="5 - 15" refId="B5742945" refString="Gogala, Matija, Trilar, Tomi, 1998. First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song. Acta Entomologica Slovenica 6 (1): 5 - 15" title="First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song" volume="6" year="1998">Gogala and Trilar (1998)</bibRefCitation>
. Some years later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="5 - 15" refId="B5742955" refString="Gogala, Matija, Trilar, Tomi, 2003. Video analysis of wing clicking in Cicadas of the genera Cicadatra and Pagiphora (Homoptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadoidea). Acta Entomologica Slovenica 11 (1): 5 - 15" title="Video analysis of wing clicking in Cicadas of the genera Cicadatra and Pagiphora (Homoptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadoidea)" volume="11" year="2003">Gogala and Trilar (2003)</bibRefCitation>
also described the mechanism of wing clicking.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
Like many other 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadatra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cicadatra" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Cicadatra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirkaldy" baseAuthorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadatra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cicadatra persica" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Cicadatra persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also has two types of songs: continuous calling song and courtship song with wing clicks. It is obvious that many species of this genus combine the normal tymbal sounds with clicks produced by wing beats against the body or substrate during their courtship song (
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="5 - 15" refId="B5742945" refString="Gogala, Matija, Trilar, Tomi, 1998. First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song. Acta Entomologica Slovenica 6 (1): 5 - 15" title="First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song" volume="6" year="1998">Gogala and Trilar 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
The phrases of a 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">continuous calling song</emphasis>
can last for many minutes without interruption (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 25" captionStartId="F5781291" captionText="Figure 25. Calling song of Cicadatra persica. (A) spectrogram and oscillogram of the selected part of the continuous calling song; (B) oscillogram of the enlarged part corresponding to the inverted window in (A)." figureDoi=".figure25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/408015" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">25</figureCitation>
). They begin without a distinct pattern of amplitude modulation and sometimes end with one or a few separate, irregular echemes. The frequency range is between 5.8 and 12.4 kHz (at -20 dB level) with maximum amplitude close to 8.4 kHz. In this wide frequency band, there are many small frequency peaks, 670-1300 Hz apart due to the ultrastructure of this song, which consists of pulses (tymbal rib clicks) with a repetition period of about 0.8 to 1.5 ms (repetition frequency 670 - 1250 Hz) (
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="5 - 15" refId="B5742945" refString="Gogala, Matija, Trilar, Tomi, 1998. First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song. Acta Entomologica Slovenica 6 (1): 5 - 15" title="First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song" volume="6" year="1998">Gogala and Trilar 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Courtship song</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 26" captionStartId="F5781295" captionText="Figure 26. Courtship song of Cicadatra persica. (A) spectrogram and oscillogram of the selected part of the courtship song accompanied by wing clicks; (B) oscillogram of the enlarged part of the courtship song accompanied by wing clicks corresponding to the inverted window in (A)." figureDoi=".figure26" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/408019" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">26</figureCitation>
) consists of phrases (duration 5-7 s, average 6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Â±">+/-</normalizedToken>
1.3 s) with a long series (N = 59 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Â±">+/-</normalizedToken>
14) of rapidly repeated wing clicks (repetition period 89 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Â±">+/-</normalizedToken>
15 ms and repetition frequency approx. 11 Hz), which ends with a loud tymbal echeme with increasing amplitude (duration 186 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Â±">+/-</normalizedToken>
26 ms). After a short pause, the wing clicks of the next phrase begin again. The first interval between the clicks is usually a bit longer and the last 2-6 intervals of a phrase are even longer. The interval between the last click and a tymbal echeme is extremely variable and can last between 60 and 600 ms. The frequency spectrum of tymbal echemes is similar to the spectrum of a continuous song, but the wing clicks have a wider frequency spectrum (2-20 kHz) with a maximum amplitude between 3 and 7 kHz (Gogala and Trilar 1998). The clicks always occur in connection with the opening and closing of the forewings. The hindwings remain more or less in the same position during this cycle (Gogala and Trilar 2003). The males singing close together often synchronise the phrases almost simultaneously, so that the tymbal echemes appear, but are slightly shifted for about 50-150 ms (Gogala and Trilar 1998).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
In addition to these two types of song, a few irregular tymbal echemes are recorded with the same spectrum as the continuous song, usually before the cicadas flew away. This may be an alarm song (rivalry song or distress call) by animals singing or courting too close together (
<bibRefCitation author="Gogala, Matija" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Slovenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424" pagination="5 - 15" refId="B5742945" refString="Gogala, Matija, Trilar, Tomi, 1998. First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song. Acta Entomologica Slovenica 6 (1): 5 - 15" title="First record of Cicadatra persica Kirkaldy, 1909 from Macedonia, with description of its song" volume="6" year="1998">Gogala and Trilar 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">
Selected sound samples of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="54424">Cicadatra persica</emphasis>
are available on the web pages 
